              {/* History */}
              <section id="history" className="mb-10">
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-serif border-b border-gray-200 pb-2 mb-4">
                  History &amp; Origins
                </h2>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  The conceptual foundation of the XRP Ledger was developed by{' '}
                  <strong>David Schwartz</strong>, <strong>Jed McCaleb</strong>, and{' '}
                  <strong>Arthur Britto</strong> in 2011–2012. At the time, Bitcoin&apos;s
                  proof-of-work model had already demonstrated the concept of decentralized
                  digital money, but its energy consumption, slow confirmation times, and
                  limited transaction throughput made it impractical for institutional
                  financial use. The three engineers designed the XRP Ledger as an alternative:
                  a consensus-based ledger that could settle transactions in seconds and handle
                  thousands of transactions per second without mining.
                </p>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  In <strong>2012</strong>, the founders gifted <strong>80 billion XRP</strong>{' '}
                  — 80% of the total fixed supply of 100 billion — to a company called{' '}
                  <strong>OpenCoin</strong>, which soon rebranded to{' '}
                  <strong>Ripple Labs</strong> (later simply <strong>Ripple</strong>). Ripple&apos;s
                  stated mission was to use XRP and the XRP Ledger as infrastructure for
                  institutional cross-border payment flows, positioning it as a neutral bridge
                  currency between fiat currencies.
                </p>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  <strong>Jed McCaleb</strong> left Ripple in 2013 and went on to co-found
                  <strong> Stellar</strong>, a competing blockchain with a similar consensus
                  architecture. He retained a substantial XRP holding that he sold over many
                  years through a structured agreement with Ripple, finally exhausting his
                  position in 2022. The departure and ongoing sale pressure from McCaleb&apos;s
                  holdings was a recurring narrative in XRP&apos;s price history throughout the
                  2014–2022 period.
                </p>
                <p className="leading-relaxed">
                  XRP reached peak prices during the <strong>2017–2018 crypto bull market</strong>,
                  briefly hitting <strong>$3.84</strong> in January 2018 before collapsing with
                  the broader market. It surged again in late <strong>2020</strong>, just before
                  the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filed its landmark lawsuit against
                  Ripple in December of that year.
                </p>
              </section>

              {/* How It Works */}
              <section id="how-it-works" className="mb-10">
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-serif border-b border-gray-200 pb-2 mb-4">
                  How XRP Works
                </h2>

                <h3 id="consensus" className="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Federated Consensus</h3>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  Unlike Bitcoin&apos;s proof-of-work or Ethereum&apos;s proof-of-stake, the
                  XRP Ledger uses a{' '}
                  <strong>Federated Byzantine Agreement (FBA)</strong> consensus model. A
                  network of independent validator nodes — operated by universities, exchanges,
                  financial institutions, and individuals — must reach supermajority agreement
                  (80%+) on each ledger version for it to close and become immutable. This
                  approach enables:
                </p>
                <ul className="list-disc ml-6 mb-4 space-y-1 leading-relaxed text-gray-800">
                  <li><strong>Transaction finality in 3–5 seconds</strong> under normal network conditions</li>
                  <li><strong>~1,500 transactions per second</strong> (upgrades targeting higher throughput)</li>
                  <li><strong>Transaction fees of ~0.00001 XRP</strong> (a fraction of a cent)</li>
                  <li><strong>No mining</strong> — negligible energy consumption versus proof-of-work chains</li>
                </ul>
                <p className="leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  Validators do not earn XRP for their participation; the model relies on
                  economic and reputational incentives for operators who benefit from a
                  healthy, functional ledger.
                </p>

                <h3 id="tokenomics" className="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Tokenomics &amp; Supply</h3>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  XRP has a <strong>fixed maximum supply of 100 billion tokens</strong>, all
                  created at genesis — no new XRP can ever be minted. Each transaction destroys
                  (burns) a tiny amount of XRP as a fee, making the total supply slowly
                  deflationary over time. As of early 2026, approximately{' '}
                  <strong>57 billion XRP are in circulation</strong>, with the remainder held
                  in escrow by Ripple under a structured monthly release schedule designed to
                  limit market impact. Ripple releases up to 1 billion XRP per month from
                  escrow; any unreleased portion is re-escrowed for future periods.
                </p>
              </section>

              {/* Ripple */}
              <section id="ripple" className="mb-10">
