              {/* SEC */}
              <section id="sec" className="mb-10">
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-serif border-b border-gray-200 pb-2 mb-4">
                  SEC Lawsuit &amp; Legal History
                </h2>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  In <strong>December 2020</strong>, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission
                  filed a lawsuit against Ripple Labs, CEO Brad Garlinghouse, and co-founder
                  Chris Larsen, alleging that Ripple had raised over{' '}
                  <strong>$1.3 billion through the unregistered sale of XRP as a security</strong>.
                  The case became one of the most consequential regulatory actions in crypto history,
                  triggering XRP delistings from major U.S. exchanges including Coinbase, Kraken,
                  and Bitstamp&apos;s U.S. platform.
                </p>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  In <strong>July 2023</strong>, Judge Analisa Torres issued a split ruling:
                  XRP sold to institutional investors was deemed to be a security (violating
                  SEC rules), but XRP sold on public exchanges to retail investors was{' '}
                  <strong>not a security</strong> — a partial but historic win for Ripple and
                  for the broader crypto industry. The ruling triggered XRP&apos;s re-listing
                  on major exchanges and a sharp price rally.
                </p>
                <p className="leading-relaxed">
                  The SEC and Ripple reached a final settlement in <strong>2024</strong>,
                  with Ripple paying a reduced penalty and the agency formally closing the
                  case. The resolution, combined with a broader shift in the SEC&apos;s posture
                  toward crypto under the incoming Trump administration, effectively ended
                  the multi-year legal overhang that had suppressed XRP adoption in
                  U.S. institutional markets.
                </p>
              </section>

