              <section id="incident-2026" className="mb-10">
                <h2 className="text-2xl font-serif border-b border-gray-200 pb-2 mb-4">
                  2026 $80B Exploit Discovery
                </h2>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  In <strong>February 2026</strong>, the XRP Ledger Foundation confirmed that
                  a critical vulnerability had been discovered in the proposed{' '}
                  <strong>Batch amendment</strong> — a protocol upgrade under validator review.
                  The flaw, identified by <strong>Cantina AI</strong> and security researcher{' '}
                  <strong>Pranamya Keshkamat</strong> on February 19, 2026, was a logic error
                  in the Batch amendment&apos;s signature validation process that would have
                  allowed an attacker to authorize transactions from any account without that
                  account&apos;s private key — effectively enabling the unauthorized draining of
                  any XRPL wallet.
                </p>
                <p className="mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  Because the flaw was caught during the <strong>validator voting phase</strong>{' '}
                  — before the amendment reached mainnet activation — no user funds were ever
                  at risk. The XRPL engineering team issued an emergency patch release
                  (<strong>rippled 3.1.1</strong>) and the Batch amendment was withdrawn from
                  the activation queue to be re-designed. The incident was widely cited as a
                  landmark example of AI-assisted security tooling preventing a potentially
                  catastrophic blockchain exploit.
                </p>
